The subject matter of the present show is early science fiction. What one identifies as early science fiction, of course, depends upon what his definition of science fiction is. If you want to call any literature of a fantastic nature science fiction, then you'd have to go back to the beginning of human expression. Consider stories of gods, creation myths, and early religions of science fiction, but we're not going to go back that far. It's more useful to place the origins of science fiction, I think, much further forward in history. At a time when the word science means something, and when the naivete and superstitions of the ancient world have mostly given way to a truer, more modern sense of reality. But to get to the present, or further forward in history, we'll have to pass over authors like Jonathan Swift, who wrote Gulliver's Travels, and Edgar Allan Poe, both of whom are considered as writing early science fiction, and move up to 1817, when Mary Shelley published what many critics would consider the first science fiction novel. And that book was Frankenstein, and the reason it's considered the first science fiction novel is that it uses science in the story, in that Frankenstein is a creature who is built, who is put together out of, I guess you could say, spare parts, and then it's brought to life by its creator. And that book was written in the book, using the scientific forces of electricity, rather than some magical force that you might find in an earlier work. But I think Shelley's treatment of her material, Mary Shelley, just the way she handled it, I think qualifies a novel to be one of science fiction. But at the time she wrote it, there was no real separation between fantastic literature and realistic literature. There was no categorizing process, and literature was simply literature. The origin of the term science fiction didn't occur until the 1920s, when for various reasons it began to exist as a separate literary category. But immediately before that time there were three major writers who had an immense influence on the field. A Frenchman, Jules Verne, an Englishman, H.G. Wells, and an American, Edgar Rice Burroughs. Jules Verne was born in 1828 and published his first science fiction book, Five Weeks in a Balloon, in 1863. A lot of people considered Verne to be a prophet for seeing a lot of the technological things that we have. Actually, I think he was more just a good science fiction writer. He took a lot of concepts that were on the verge of coming about, things like the electric light, the submarine and air travel, explorations that were going on. He took all of these elements, some scientific, some geographical, and physics and other types of scientific accoutrements, and blended them into an adventure story format. I think maybe this is one of the prime or primal manifestations of science fiction as a form in itself. You could almost say that for his own time he would be a hard science fiction writer in that almost all of his stories, as you say, they had a great deal of adventure or reader interest, but they also were based on some sort of scientific concept. Say, the giant cannon in the book, From the Earth to the Moon, from which they made a movie. He goes into long explanations on the acceleration needed to reach the moon, the muzzle velocity of the cannon to shoot the projectile. So, really, fairly definite science for his day. That's true, although some of the science as seen today is, I guess you could call it a little dated, his cannon to shoot people to the moon. But many of the things he wrote were very well thought out, such as in 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea, his extremely powerful, highly developed submarine that traveled around the world, mostly underwater, harkens to today's nuclear-powered submarines. Of course, he created an unforgettable character in that book, Captain Nemo, almost the archetype of the mysterious, powerful scientist who is living by himself, conducting experiments. I think that fascinates a lot of readers of the book and viewers, of course, of the movie, too. That's true. He was an extremely well-developed character, and more is told about him in the sequel to 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea, Mysterious Island. In Mysterious Island, we see a lighter vein of work that Vern was caught up in in a lot of his earlier works, the bohemian, romantic type of castaway on a lost island somewhere, Robinson Crusoe-type stories. There are quite a few of these in his earlier works.
